 &quot;Don't do that, Sarah...&quot; Dean started. &quot;Rylen is gonna hurt you again. I can only be here for some times, bu-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He won't do it again, really!&quot; She stamerred.<br>
<br>
&quot;Saah... Have you even seen this guy?&quot; He sighed into the reciever.<br>
<br>
&quot;.....No, but-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;WHAT THE HELL!? I thought you met this guy, like he lived in Granite of something. But you've *never* even *SEEN* him?&quot; He was getting irate very quickly. &quot;Please tell me you got a pic, a REAL pic, at least?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot; She shuffled the phone around. &quot;Look, my dad needs the phone, so we'll carry this conversation on tomorrow, ok?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Fine. Peace.&quot; Dean hit the button, and the telephone beeped off. Great. Sarah was going back to Rylen. ~Seems like everything really does elude my grasp.... Does God *really* like me, or am I *really* just that lucky?~<br>
<br>
&quot;I've had enough of this.&quot; He moved his aching back off the recliner &amp; strode around the wooden counter. He planted the phone back on the charger, slipped on his Vans, and walked out of the house. He forgot a shirt. He forgot to take his dog chain back off. He forgot that he had two knives strapped to his belt...<br>
<br>
He seemed oblivious to it all. Dean wasn't in the real world anymore, anyways. Slipknot was playing in the background as he closed the door to his apartment. &quot;This is a seed, It festers and breathes, My heros are dead, They died in my head....&quot; He scared Mrs. Weatherbee, as he constantly does, with his spiked, black hair and menacing, red eyes. He changed them on occasion. ~Thank Loki for tha spells...~ Dean thought.<br>
<br>
After he walked out of the building, he realized he wasn't even out on the streets. There was no blackened trash cans. No mail boxes, cars, lamp posts... The wind blowing didn't carry the stench of exhaust and at least a few newspapers on it. Instead, the aroma of stagnating hot dogs from a corner vendor was replaced by the scintilating smells of fresh daisies. The stars were shining, more brightly than most nights... The canopy of green was scattered, only letting a few glimpses show every so often. It was almost uniform, the way the forest made her light shows...<br>
<br>
~I looked to the ground. Fresh dirt &amp; grasses underfoot, along with ivy, belltops, &amp; the sporadic mulberry bushes, were all I could see. The low hum of the lamplights and cars were now a breeze russling the leaves. I breathed in the fresh air deeply, and sighed. Tranquillity...~<br>
<br>
Dean was walking along Dunn, incoherent to his surroundings. An officer rode past, barely noticing a man shuffling along, seemingly out of place of his surroundings. Nothing unusual here...<br>
<br>
It was about midnight. Most people were in bed, or rushing off to bed. Or partying. Either way, not many street crawlers were out prowling, &amp; backed away from the short, muscular, well-armed freak. Baggy pants can conceal all kinds of guns, after all... Dean turned the corner, out onto main street. He was going towards Cherr Crop, the only real strip joint around.<br>
<br>
~I heard dull echoes in the distance... laughter? Of course, the elves were always joyful, active in their nightlife. It made perfect sense. I ran towards them. A flashing light blinded me, as if it were a warning drone. I'd encountered them before. I promptly threw a dagger at it, to the upper right corner, and it swerved away, injured, no longer interested in me. Foolish sentries.~<br>
<br>
After a dagger plunked into the man's shoulder, pinning him to the seat, the Ford F250 ran onto the sidewalk, crushing a local drunk. He didn't know what was coming upon him, though, as he was preoccupied with the millions of ants trying to get into his skin. Dean marched on.<br>
<br>
The red eyed freak finally came to the door of Cherr Crop. Dean wasn't concerned with the bouncer, though. He smiled curtly to the hulking white man, bald, &amp; with a pair of studded rings on each hand. Dean jumped onto his shoulder, spun around, and caught a fire ladder before the big man could react. He looked up, saw the shirtless clown shimmying up the ladder, and decided he was cool to pass.<br>
<br>
Dean got to the roof, three stories up. He knew this level quite well; it was the rave level. Bright lights, techno beats, &amp; all kinds of drugs were all that really mattered in the dark room. Flashes. Sounds. Touch. Smoke. Repeat.... Dean had more important things to do. He dragged off of a dooby, &amp; passed it on, thinking this literal roach didn't like being burned alive much, &amp; thought the elves may stick to their customs. <br>
<br>
