<br>
&quot;Step from th' bar and the ladies, Targon. We shan't have more of your treachery this night.&quot; I spat upon his shadow silk boots. &quot;Leave, lest this bar become a bloodbath.&quot;~<br>
<br>
The dirty drunk named John Assler, commonly known as Targon in Cherr Crop nowadays, stroked his brownish-black stubble that grew on his pale chin. It seemed as if that was the only hair that contained color on his entire body. His hair was, indeed, long and white. The black gloves on his hands only added to Dean's proclomation (in his own reality, that is) that this man was surely a dark elf. Barbarians and ogres filled the tavern, yes, and human girls danced upon the stage with lights and poles and little (if any) clothing, but Dean's attention was rivetted at this man.<br>
<br>
&quot;I beseech thee one last chance, drow...&quot; Dean crouched into a fighting stance, leading with his left foot, hands straight and stiff. The four feet between them seemed infinitely smaller as the crowd gathered around. They've all seen this fight before, so most just went back to their private parties or staring at the dancing girls.<br>
<br>
The wooden floors creaked as John stepped away from the bar. He kicked his stool back, saying, &quot;This is America. This is a free country. I'll hit yer ass with a lawsuit so fast-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Then why haven'tCHA, Johnnay?&quot; an onlooker mused.<br>
<br>
John frowned. He knew he was beat, &amp; he'd been kicked out of all the other joints and bars around town for scraps or too much drinking. It wasn't his fault he was a bad drunk, really...<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm not leavin, kid, so...&quot; John spoke as he slowly turned towards the counter again, &amp; grabbed a bottle. He spun and swung at Dean while shouting, &quot;LEAVE ME ALONE!&quot;<br>
