 ~Targon fell, and I was atop him in moments. The fight ended shortly thereafter, as I disposed of the savage creation. The beast, the vile drow that all the elven races hated at birth, fell beneath my fang. His crimson life force spilled onto the floor for the last time, and I was hauled to my feet before I was even allowed to taste the sweet, salty blessing of victory. In mid-lap I was carried by the bouncers from the front. Never before had they the gall to assault me; why now? Why, after I had disposed of the greatest enemy of all the Wakening Lands? Why?~<br>
<br>
Dean was hoisted to his feet by two burly bouncers. Both were bald, both in open shirts, but the white one had nearly two hundred pounds over his leaner co-worker. The burly mexican held the people back with his other arm as he lifted Dean's left side. Blood ran down the young man's bare chest, and his knife was clutched in the other massive bouncer's hand. Together, they made their way through the the throng of people crowding around. They were like jackals, all of them, waiting for a feast of the eyes, and Dean gave them one... oh yes, he did. There were no virgin eyes after this night (if you could consider them virgin eyes in Cherr Crop)<br>
<br>
By the time he was hauled up to Mike, Dean was in a fury. Another bouncer joined in the carrying of the tiny, enraged man. Mike wasn't in the least bit surprised to see blood streaming down his chest. His eyes went wide when he was told by the knife-clutching bouncer what exactly Dean did.<br>
<br>
&quot;He straight up *bit* tha @#%$'s neck off, boss,&quot; He said.<br>
<br>
Mike's eyes went wide. His peaceful, Bob Marley attitude was replaced by a wide-eyed look of fear. &quot;H-he... he... what?&quot;<br>
<br>
The other bouncer, now restraining Dean totally in a full nelson while the other grabbed his thrashing feet, cried, &quot;He killed him! He killed that Targon dude, man!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;John Assler...&quot; A tall, lanky whie man with a long white beard crept out from around a corner, and Dean became suddenly still. His eyes went from the blood red they had glowed to previously to a deep, understanding brown. &quot;His real name was John Assler.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But then-&quot;<br>
<br>
Big Mike was cut off by the stranger. &quot;Dean, in case you couldn't tell from the garb, manner, etiquette, and all around accent, is not quite... sane.&quot; He strode around to the bouncer holding Dean's legs, and eased the young man's feet back to solid tile. &quot;At least, not in this state.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, he sure as hell seems to know you.&quot; Dean's eyes were wide and star-spangled; he was oblivious to &quot;Michaelangelo's&quot; words.<br>
<br>
&quot;The great Zedicuss Zu'ul Zorander...&quot; Dean whispered. His tough, near-black spikes began softening. &quot;Wizard of the First Order...&quot; Breaking the bouncer's now relaxed hold, he kneeled, fist to his heart, and bowed his head low.<br>
<br>
Turning back from the spectacle, the lanky old man garbed in a black trenchcoat and hat that covered all his features, spoke to Big Mike. &quot;He knows things. Granted, not accurately and not of any relevance in this world, but if he were interpreted, and things put into *our* terms, he would be a sort of prophet.&quot; A bewildered look crossed Big Mike's face. The man removed his hat and opened his coat. Beneath was an armani suit, neatly pressed.<br>
<br>
&quot;John Assler, or Targon in Dean's mind,&quot; he began while striding towards the band, &quot;Was a dark elf, or drow, and would have killed you and your entire club. Truth be told, John Assler was just some poor schmuck, down on his luck, that was ready to shoot up the bar before Dean interfered each time. The previous two times he just felt sorry for himself to be taken by a younger man, deepening his self-pity.&quot; He lit a cigarette, and tossed the remaining pack of Marlboro Reds to a table nearby. A punk woman, mid twenties, with spiked red &amp; white hair and a leather skirt, picked it up and walked off with it. He didn't seem to notice, or care either way. &quot;Dean stopped it. In his mind, he knew. In our world, he knew. Though the reasons were different, the results would have been the same.&quot;<br>
<br>
He turned back towards the bouncers who appeared to be dozing off, and promptly shoved each of them. &quot;You appear to him as orcs or ogres of some sort.&quot; Then he turned to Big Mike and the fat dooby in his hand. &quot;And you are an elf king, kissing your ring and breathing magic into the air. Though these ideas make no sense here, they make perfect sense to him, &amp; the basic ideas get through. He just makes things more... fantasy-like.&quot;<br>
<br>
~I knew the signal well. I thought I saw it three times before, but I knew it too well. Perhaps the Great Wizard was testing me this time. Yes, that was it. He was testing me. I knew the signal from the dreams he kept sending me. Yes, First Wizard Zorander sent me the dreams, I knew it now! It all made perfect sense. The puff of smoke came again. It was the wrong shape, but it went in the right direction. The next was probably it...<br>
<br>
The snake smog. That was the signal.<br>
<br>
*GO!!!*<br>
<br>
Before the ogre guards could grab a hold of me, I had my dirk in hand again &amp; was vaulting up the musical constructs. These artifact walls produced sound at a high rate. If I could only ride on the notes of the bards... Would it work? Of course. Wizard Zorander would assist me here. He would make them solid for me, but *they* wouldn't know.<br>
<br>
How could I be so STUPID!? Elves are fickle people, now...<br>
<br>
But why would the death of a foe be taken so badly?<br>
<br>
I leapt. The ogres didn't have a chance. The musical constructs toppled to the floor as the blumbering buffoons crashed into it in an attempt to apprehend me. Fools, all. I had Wizard Zorander on my side, disguised though he be...<br>
<br>
The notes constructed to solidity underneath my feet. Before the holding spell wore through, though, I leaped again, this time catching the vines in the trees above. Nature and science all in one place; ah, the possibilities of this new world we live in. Perhaps I should speak with Urza, after all.<br>
