His eyes moved over to a dark figure, sprawled across the ground. His jeans had been blown away, along with all the hair on the front of his body, and any remnants of clothing were smoking and blackened. He's the only one whole, Brian realized. He crept over, stepping across a McDonald's wrapper and some empty packages of kid's toys. They were still smoldering too.<br>
<br>
Staring down at the smoking face and bullet riddled body, recognition finally crept across Brian's face; Dean! His wounds were mostly coagulated from the blast that seemed to rip from the entire front of his body, but blood still flowed sparingly. Carrying him bride-and-groom style, Brian ran into the streets, shouting, &quot;NINE-ONE-ONE!!&quot; Hell, it was dialed commonly enough in the area, after all...<br>
<br>
He looked to the right, and up the sidewalk where he had come from, and an old man in a sweatshirt and plaid vest with dusted gray slacks looked at him wide-eyed. He said, &quot;Here, get him in the car, quick!&quot;<br>
<br>
Brian settled Dean down into the car, thanking the &quot;dark-skinned stranger&quot; for his help. Brian slammed the door shut quickly, and jumped into the passenger seat. Speeding through the, luckily, uncrowded city streets like a bat outta hell, they made it to the nearest hospital in five minutes. Brian rushed him in, and thanked the old man again. He rushed in through the automatic doors screaming, &quot;SOMEONE HELP!&quot; <br>
<br>
Surreal, 6/21/2<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 He opened his eyes slowly. White light poured in, and the scent of sterilization filled his nostrils. His senses were horribley deprived in here, considering the workout they get on the streets. He missed the millions of sights and smells bombarding him at once...<br>
<br>
Then he tried to sit up. Red, hot lightning flashed through his torso. He screamed like a banshee as he felt the searing pain rip down to his toes, up to the top of his head, then doubling back to ensure maximum discomfort. His head reeled, and everything looked so incredibley surreal... but Dean knew this wasn't one of his episodes. This was unnatural. He could feel the stink in his nose, the contamination in his body, of the chemicals that flowed through his veins.<br>
<br>
He felt the IV in his arm acutely. The flow of morphine, or whatever that feel-good drug was, felt heightened, and the pain subsided; slow, achingly slow, but it ended.<br>
<br>
Dean looked around at his surroundings. There was nothing but white in here; white sheets, white curtains, white marble, white lights, white desk... there was a bit of brown on the desk, the tiny television set in front of him, and the flowers on the desk gave the only flash of color in the room.<br>
<br>
It hit him like a flash; he was in a hospital. Dean doesn't *DO* hospitals. Aggravated beyond the word &quot;anger&quot;, he tried to sit up again, thinking himself stronger than the searing flashes he felt. Struggling to his feet, and growling all the way, Dean inched towards the door, step by step, and tore off the gauze. The remaining three feet seemed infinite in his intoxicated stupor. Dean realized he was dragging the IV behind him, and tore the tube out of his arm with a vengeance; only then did he notice the blood pouring out of seven, exact, precicely round holes. They were scattered around, one in the center of the chest, three on the right side and shoulder, one to the left of the navel, and two on the left breast, just above the nipple. Startled by his previously unseen wounds, Dean started feeling incredibley woozy.<br>
<br>
The room started to spin. The lights all came in from every different angle, and Dean's vision went hazy. He fell forward, still convinced he was just fine, and caught the door handle. It flew open with his body weight, and he fell onto the sterile marble tile that led out of the room. He didn't even notice the machines in his room before, but they were all beeping and blaring now. God damn it. Who turned out the lights?<br>
<br>
Three days earlier, Brian had brought him in. They started screaming and rushing into action, like most doctors do. They bombarded him with questions... &quot;What's his name?&quot; &quot;Has he been doing any drugs?&quot; &quot;Who is his next of kin?&quot; &quot;Where did you find him?&quot; &quot;What the HELL happened?&quot;<br>
<br>
After the initial drama, when Dean was brought into the emergency room, Brian started making some phone calls. They had his residence, as well as a number found in his back pocket; in the last remnants of clothes that weren't scorched. He started with that number.<br>
<br>
The phone rang next to Frosty's ear, making him jump. The biological refrigerant he'd been working on shattered in the beaker, and he cursed the gods of the sun. Picking up the phone that had never rung before, Frosty growled, &quot;What?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Is this, uh, Frosty?&quot; a voice asked from the reciever.<br>
<br>
Gritting his teeth and uttering a guteral rumble, he half-grunted, &quot;Goway!&quot; He put on the white beater to cover the scars that glowed with a blue luminescence. He walked out into the not-so-airconditioned hallway and started sweating. Stalking into the room, the phone rang again. A nervous twitch visited Frosty's eye. He picked it up, and nearly yelled, &quot;What!?&quot;<br>
<br>
From the other end, he heard a voice saying, &quot;This is the Greenview Hospital. Is there any kin of a Dean.... Scram... Cross-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yea yea, whaddya want? What the hell did he do now?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Thought that might keep you from hangin up on me,&quot; the voice chuckled. &quot;My name's Brian. I'm a... colleague, you could say, of Dean's.&quot; Frosty grunted his acknoledgement. &quot;He's been shot...... Hello? ....Hello?&quot;<br>
<br>
Frosty had already jumping out the window.<br>
<br>
Brian and Frosty both saw Dean as he stumbled out of the room, bathing the floor in blood. They had just picked him up when a flurry of nurses lifted him from their arms and set him on the bed, reattatching this, refilling that. They finally got him back in shape, and closed the door behind them. <br>
<br>
Surreal, 6/22/2<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 &quot;How did he jump out?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That's not a problem. He does it all the time.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;:: grunts ::&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The big question is.... how the hell did he live through that?&quot;<br>
<br>
Brian chuckled at the blue man that seemed to glow every now and then. &quot;I figured you of all people would have known that,&quot;<br>
<br>
Frosty's eyebrow went up. He sat down on the now empty bed, and took a bite out of his hamburger. Sipping the coke, he swallowed. Around the remaining mixture of food, he growled, &quot;Tha fffffukk izat s'posed ta mean?&quot;<br>
<br>
Brian stared blankly at him. The little man with blue eyes stared into his very soul, and seemed to freeze it. Running a hand through his long black hair, which was taken out of his fighter's crop when he came to the hospital, he took a critical glance at this oddly dangerous man. He seemed to move with a grace and confidence unkown to most men. It was as if his every action was cold, calculated, and efficient. He even sat with awareness, like a fight could spring up at any moment. Shaking off the shock, he remembered the question. Continuing to chew the onion ring, he swallowed hard.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ahem. Well, uh... the... magic... thing?&quot; Frosty stared blankly at him. &quot;The reason you glow? The spell?&quot; Brian was getting nowhere.<br>
<br>
He ran his fingers through his hair again. Before he got started, Frosty cut him off. Standing from the bloody bed, he asked, &quot;Magic? You seriously expect me to believe that?&quot;<br>
<br>
Brian laughed aloud. If only Urza was here to explain this... A blade was at his throat, and his laugh was cut short. Frosty's menacing grin returned, inches from the cornered monk's face, and the blue glow from behind his teeth gave Frosty an ice-like quality. As if his cold skin didn't already... &quot;Talk.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Magic! It-it's real, it-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Stutter, and I dig in deeper. Repeat yourself, and I dig in deeper.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;YES! Ok.&quot; Brian swallowed to keep himself from stammering all over the place. &quot;Magic... can be done. It's possible. But only if you believe it can. Without belief, you can do none of it.&quot;<br>
<br>
The blade dropped. Frosty hooked a finger under his collar, and wiped a bit of sweat from his forehead. &quot;Now, why didn't you just blaze me with a fireball or something if you believe it can be done?&quot;<br>
<br>
Brian grinned evilly. His dark gaze settled on the blue assassin, and the black hair framing chizled face gave a vibe of total malice. &quot;Because I didn't have my lighter.&quot; The zippo appeared in his hand almost instantly, and Brian flicked the top open and sparked it up with one motion. The flame appeared, and Frosty's eyes went wide. Fire. Death. Fire. Death. FIRE!<br>
<br>
Waves of heat shimmered around the blue assassin. His body needed extreme cool, but this was... HOT! Brian's hair lifted with the heat, like it was making it wave in the air. He extended his middle and forefinger together, and flipped his wrist up. Heat seared upwards, and the room flared red. Curtains and sheets caught fire. &quot;Hot enough for ya?&quot;<br>
<br>
Roaring with the fury of a caged animal near its death, Frosty threw off his trenchcoat. The blue luminescent scars glowed with unmatched brilliance, staining the light purple. As Brian's hair settled down, the blue won over, and the room turned quite cool. The small flames that caught smoldered down and smoked. The air got uncomfortably chilly, but Frosty didn't mind. The blue glow stopped, and so did his voice. Looking up, bewilderment showing in his emotionless eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Did you feel that wave of power pass through you?&quot; Frosty nodded. &quot;That was the will; what makes the magic work. I don't care whether you believe it or not, but you *are* magic. The glow? The external coolant? Maybe not if you believe, but if you *need* it, you'll have your magic.&quot;<br>
<br>
Frosty ran a hand through his blue spikes. He picked up his trenchcoat, and started walking to the window. Regaining his confidence, he snarled, &quot;He went this way. I can find him.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How?&quot;<br>
<br>
He sneered back, &quot;Maaaaaagic? No! That's horsesht. Red can do it,&quot; Frosty tapped his shoulder, and the window blew open. In flew a little black goblin.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ta-daaaaaaaaaaaah~!!&quot; he shouted.<br>
<br>
Brian raised an eyebrow, but didn't feel like starting up the magic issue again. Frosty saw the puzzled look, and stated, &quot;It's. Not. Magic. Innate abilities, maybe. Tricks, skills, techniques. Don't call it magic; it sounds so god damned stupid.&quot; Brian shrugged, and they walked down the fire escape. &quot;Now,&quot; Frosty asked, &quot;Again. How'd he live?&quot;<br>
<br>
Brian climbed down the rusty ladder, following the inane ramblings of the dark gnome. &quot;He exerted a massive blast of energy, one he most likely thought was his last. He probably expended his mental energy all on that blast. It cauterized(sp?) the wounds, killed the dealers, and blasted into some buildings. As far as the rapid healing...&quot; They stopped while Red sniffed at the ground near a street light. Frosty looked at the monk, who shrugged.<br>
<br>
&quot;Dude! He's back at his apartment. Duh!&quot; Red stood, regaining composure and sophistication. Brian now saw the intelligence, not merely a pet. &quot;Anyways. I have a few matters in the outer fringe of Nebtulos. A few darker garinjahs have decided to start trouble and break the peace treaty struck in Hoolloo Gnosis. We got another resource war on our hands.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The garinjahs? I thought they were allied with nurr'ok forces.&quot; Frosty turned a quizzical eye on his miniscule friend.<br>
<br>
&quot;They were. They think their materialistic views of the mining and technological advances taken towards the mining of the tin give them the upper hand.&quot; He glanced to Brian, then back at Frosty. &quot;Pff. Some races think all might goes to science and technology. They don't understand the value of aetheric balances and psychic manipulations, or projection of will.&quot; Red went back to muttering dark equations drawn in the shadow of the two big men. Dean rounded the corner, seven scars on his chest.<br>
<br>
&quot;Actually, science and magick is closely linked, Red. The only problem is that humans are one of the few races that believe their minds aren't capable of projecting their will. They don't believe what they can't see or prove. Others believe only in that. Not enough blending.&quot; The darkling took in the friendly face with a toothy grin.<br>
<br>
